[Student "S"]
{South is to play 7NT. West leads the \HK.

With 12 obvious tricks your first thought should be that perhaps the \Ss will split 3-3.

Then, your second thought should be that dummy's \HJ is a Threat against West's \HQ, so if it is West who holds 4 \Ss you will be able to squeeze him.

Since the contract is 7NT you take the first trick with the \HA. 

With one trick in the bag you should test \Ds next. When you play the \DA East discards a \S.

You continue with the \DQ and \D K, East discarding a \H and a \C. 

Since East has shown up with a \D void he has become the odds-on favorite to hold the \S Guard. His \S discard makes it very likely that he started with 5 \Ss. 

To find out for sure you play \SA, then \SQ. Sure enough West discards a \H on the second round. 

You can't squeeze West in \Hs and \Ss because he doesn't hold the \S Guard, East does. 

But now a completely new possibility shows up. Say to yourself, over and over, "West must guard \Hs, and East must guard \Ss. Nobody can guard \Cs."

You start playing dummy's \D winners. 

With one more \D in dummy, things look like this. 

When you play the \D5 East must keep both \Ss to guard against your \S7. So he discards the \C6, hoping partner can stop that suit.

Your \S7 is now worthless so you throw it.

West has no problem, (yet), he discards the \H10. 

[showcards N:S5,HJ,CK,C7 E:SJ,ST,CQ,CT S:SK,CA,C8,C4 W:HQ,CJ,C9,C5]

It is now time to pressure West. 

Play dummy's \S5 to your \SK.

West MUST keep his \HQ so he releases his \C5.

And you win the last three tricks with \CK, \CA, \C8.

This is called a Double Squeeze.}
[Play "W"]HK

